Colored pencils are versatile and precise. Enhance your drawing repertoire with gem-like sticks of color! In this four-week class, we'll start with exercises to create our own color charts that explore blending, alternate finishes, and texture. Next we will sketch from a basic still-life. Then we'll work on an exquisite rendering from a landscape photo for the last two meetings. Photo references will be provided, but instead you may certainly work from a picture that you have at home. There will be time for critiques and sharing our work with the class at the end of each session. Please bring materials to class. Materials list available at sharonartstudio.org.

Karate originated in the Okinawa Islands of Japan and has branched out into many different styles. Karate Kidz is a structured class that teaches formalized, sequenced movements which represent offensive and defensive postures known as Kata. Students will also learn kicking, punching, blocking and other open hand techniques. Students will have the opportunity to purchase a uniform and belts for an extra fee.

event_description: **You are adding to the wait list only**The After School program is currently full. You are adding to the wait list for the 2025-26 school year. If a spot opens up and we are able to offer you a spot, we will reach out. This afterschool program only pick up participants from Sunnyside.Our after school program is an experience that provides a safe and    nurturing environment for youth in grades K-5 to develop life long recreation    and leisure skills. Participants will receive homework assistance, be exposed to an    environment that will promote literacy, encourage communication and    empowerment skills while providing recreation activities that include sports,    group games, arts and culture, community exploration and seasonal special    events. All staff and volunteers receive background checks and are trained in    safety skills. Start times may vary based on the school release time. The fee    for the school year is $1,080. Parents will have the option to pay the entire    fee upon registration. Payment plans are available. $270 is due upon registration    and on the first day of October, January and March of the school year.

Discover    the mesmerizing art of marbling in this hands-on workshop. Participants will    explore traditional and contemporary marbling techniques, learning how to    create flowing, one-of-a-kind patterns on paper and fabric using paints and    specialized tools. Guided step by step, you’ll experiment with color,    movement, and composition while gaining an understanding of the materials and    processes behind this centuries-old craft. No prior experience is    necessary—just curiosity and a willingness to play. The workshop offers a    relaxed, creative environment where you can slow down, enjoy the meditative    rhythm of marbling, and leave with several finished pieces to take home.    Perfect for artists, crafters, or anyone looking for a unique and inspiring    creative experience.

event_name: Woodworking in Small Spaces: Portable Workbenches!
event_description: Are you    interested in woodworking but like most city residents have limited space?    Have you built saw horses at the Randall and want to explore how to put them    to use? In this hands-on class you'll build a portable workbench that can    mount on those saw horses or at your kitchen table. From the classic hand    tools needed to make furniture (chisels, hand planes, measuring and marking    tools, and various types of saws) to small, portable power tools, you'll go    home with a deeper sense of what's possible in small spaces. Instructor Mike    Bray has decades of experience and scores of tricks and techniques for    working safely and accurately. A $100 materials fee is included in the cost    and covers the unique demands of the bench, including a bench vise, two    layers of finished ply, and hardwood framing. Prerequisite: Woodshop Safety    Orientation. Students who have not met the prerequisite will be withdrawn and    charged a 20% refund processing fee.

The primary purpose of the lifeguard training program is to provide entry-level lifeguard skills and knowledge to prevent, recognize, and respond to emergencies and to provide care for sudden illnesses until advanced medical personnel arrives and takes over. This program includes a lifeguard training course with aquatics-specific first aid and cardio-pulmonary resuscitation (CPR) training. Note: Participants MUST pass the pre-test on the first day of class. The test consists of the following: 300-yard swim; tread water for 2 minute without the use of arms; swim 20 yards, then surface dive to retrieve a 10-lb brick, swim back to the starting point with both hands on the brick, and climb out of the water without assistance, skill must be performed in under 1 minute 40 seconds. Depending on the skills of the participants and their comprehension of the materials presented, the participants may be dismissed early or need to stay later each day.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

event_name: Mixed Media: Abstract and Figure-Hybrid Art
event_description: This    class emphasizes the power of inner vision—creating images from within,    rather than simply copying nature. While we will begin by studying and    imitating existing forms, the focus will shift toward transforming those    observations into original, expressive creations. The main goal of this    course is for students to discover their own unique visual style. By    exploring Surrealist, Cubist, and imitating ancient artistic influences,    students will experience the joy of creative transformation within oneself.      Students will first learn the principles of abstract geometric composition,    then move toward combining figurative or organic elements with abstraction.    The aim is to develop an individual artistic “flavor”—a step toward personal    originality.      Hands-on support will be provided throughout. No prior experience is    necessary. A $138 Model fee included in the price of the class. Please bring    supplies to class. Materials list available at sharonartstudio.org.

Discover    the mesmerizing art of marbling in this hands-on workshop. Participants will    explore traditional and contemporary marbling techniques, learning how to    create flowing, one-of-a-kind patterns on paper and fabric using paints and    specialized tools. Guided step by step, you’ll experiment with color,    movement, and composition while gaining an understanding of the materials and    processes behind this centuries-old craft. No prior experience is    necessary—just curiosity and a willingness to play. The workshop offers a    relaxed, creative environment where you can slow down, enjoy the meditative    rhythm of marbling, and leave with several finished pieces to take home.    Perfect for artists, crafters, or anyone looking for a unique and inspiring    creative experience.

Karate originated in the Okinawa Islands of Japan and has branched out into many different styles. Karate Kidz is a structured class that teaches formalized, sequenced movements which represent offensive and defensive postures known as Kata. Students will also learn kicking, punching, blocking and other open hand techniques. Students will have the opportunity to purchase a uniform and belts for an extra fee.

Got a favorite movie? Ever wonder how the great movies got their magic? This class teaches you how! This class is an exploration of cinema style and technique through replication, imitation, creation of cinema, movies, TV, and net series. The class watches and analyzes famous movies, focusing on specific techniques, which they then replicate in class. First we watch it, then we do it! This class will use short scenes, script analysis, making short-films, lighting, camera drills, and students will practice acting/blocking tactics for movie success.

Are you    retired and looking for something new to explore?  Do you have time on a Tuesday afternoon and    are curious about trying drawing and painting in a fun, laid back    environment? Are you wanting to connect with your intuition, play, or    destress using art as a vehicle?     Playful Intuitive Art Exploration is a fun and exploratory drawing and    painting class that gives folks an opportunity to express themselves    creatively through creating art and connecting with their intuition. We will    be taking inspiration from unique real-world images (centered around nature    and microscopic photography) which incorporate interesting colors, textures,    and shapes. You will learn basic drawing techniques using the elements of art    and will be experimenting with abstract and representational concepts using    your intuition as a guide. You get to be the orchestrator here. There is no    right or wrong in this class and no prior drawing experience is necessary!    Join us and have some fun!

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

Come    learn the potter's wheel with us! This friendly & supportive studio is    the perfect place to develop your throwing skills. You'll learn to wedge,    center, and pull up the clay walls of your wheel-thrown clay pieces. Begin    throwing cups & bowls and progress at your own pace to more advanced    forms like vases and plates. You'll learn glazing techniques, and work will    be fired in the Randall kilns. NOTE: New students must attend the first three    class meetings.

Come to a  place where we build Deaf community, language and culture. The    Deaf Club will be meeting once a month on the first Friday of each month    during the season. This space provides time for Deaf community members and their    families, as well as anyone interested in engaging in Deaf culture and    developing American Sign Language skills.  The first    half of the evening is designed to support those learning American Sign    Language (ASL), including ASL students, and parents who have a child who is    Deaf or hard of hearing.  The second half of the evening is focused on    providing a space for members of the Deaf community, to share culture,    resources and socialize in a sign language-only environment.  Anyone is    welcome to stay for the second half of the evening; but they should be    prepared to hold their own in conversation.  This is a drop-in program,    but a Recreation and Parks Play Pass or sign-in is required.

There is much more in Hatha yoga practice than poses. In this series, we still explore practices aimed to improve our physical well-being through asanas (poses); we also introduce practices that include pranayama (breath expansion) techniques, and finally we experience the benefits of simple meditation techniques. The intention is awareness at a physical, mental and emotional level on as well as off the mat.

event_name: First Steps Excelsior (Playgroup, English, Spanish, Cantonese, Vietnamese)
event_description: Build healthy bonding and enjoy fun activities together, while learning about your child’s cognitive and emotional development. Activities include arts, movement, songs, and stories. For ages 6 – 36 months + parents/caregivers. Free to enroll! Please note: due to our small class size, we ask families to register only for the classes you are able to attend. If you are no longer able to attend a class, please cancel your registration or contact us at firststeps@fccenters.org. Thank you! Registration will open at 9:00 am on the 28th of each month.   ·Portola: Mondays and Wednesdays, 9:00-10:30 am · Excelsior: Tuesdays and Thursdays, 9:00-10:30 am · Visitacion Valley: Thursdays, 9:30-11:00 am. (18-36 months + caregiver) For more information or to join, contact Elsa at 415.715.6746 or firststeps@fccenters.org • • • Primeros Pasos (First Steps) es un espacio para que las familias aprendan juntas. Las maestras lo guiarán a usted y a sus pequeños a través de actividades que incluyen canciones, bailes, y lecturas divertidas. Para edades de 6–36 meses + cuidador/a. Gratis para inscribirse. Tenga en cuenta: debido a nuestro pequeño tamaño de clase, le pedimos a las familias que se registren solo para las clases a las que puede asistir. Si ya no puede asistir a una clase, cancele su registro o contáctenos en firststeps@fccenters.org. ¡Gracias! Las inscripciones se abrirán el día 28 de cada mes a las 9 de la mañana. • • • First Steps是適合孩子和家長一起學習的遊戲小組。 我們的老師將與您們一起歌曲、舞蹈、閲讀等活動。 免費報名。適合6-36個月的孩子 + 家長/監護人。 請注意：由於我們的班級規模較小，我們要求家庭只註冊您可以參加的課程。 如果您不能再上課，請取消註冊或通過 firststeps@fccenters.org 聯繫我們。 謝謝你! 每月28日上午9:00開始報名。 • • • First Steps là một nhóm trẻ mẫu giáo được giám sát bởi người lớn để các gia đình học tập cùng nhau. Các giáo viên của chúng tôi sẽ hướng dẫn bạn và con bạn thông qua các hoạt động hấp dẫn liên quan đến bài hát, điệu nhảy ngộ nghĩnh. Từ 6-36 tháng tuổi + cha mẹ/người chăm sóc. Ghi danh miễn phí. Xin lưu ý: do quy mô lớp học nhỏ, chúng tôi yêu cầu các gia đình chỉ đăng ký cho các lớp học mà bạn có thể tham dự. Nếu bạn không thể tham gia lớp học được nữa, vui lòng hủy đăng ký hoặc liên hệ với chúng tôi tại firststeps@fccenters.org. Cảm ơn! Cổng đăng ký sẽ mở vào lúc 9:00 sáng ngày 28 hàng tháng.

Through hands-on activities, guided play, and expert tips, you’ll discover how everyday moments can become powerful opportunities for learning and connection. Perfect for parents and caregivers of young children looking to build skills, confidence, and joyful bonds. Únase a nosotros en un grupo divertido y atractivo en el que los cuidadores aprenden a jugar con sus hijos de formas que favorecen las etapas y los hitos clave del desarrollo. A través de actividades prácticas, juegos guiados y consejos de expertos, descubrirá cómo los momentos cotidianos pueden convertirse en poderosas oportunidades para el aprendizaje y la conexión. Perfecto para padres y cuidadores de niños pequeños que desean desarrollar habilidades, confianza y vínculos afectivos.   0-18 months Play group / Grupo de juego para niños de 0 a 18 meses Dates/ day(s): Tuesday / Fechas/días: Martes. event_name: Adult Swim - Improving Skills and Swimming Strokes
event_description: This class seeks to improve participants' proficiency in basic aquatic skills (including rotary breathing, surface dives and treading) and the six basic swimming strokes (i.e., front crawl, back crawl, butterfly, breaststroke, elementary backstroke and sidestroke). (The butterfly stroke is optional.) Participants also learn skills and concepts needed to stay safe around water, in addition to those needed to help themselves or others in an aquatic emergency.

In this    course you will learn the basic skills and fundamentals of indoor rock    climbing: from learning how to secure your harness to learning basic climbing    techniques. Participants will be introduced to knot school and top-rope    belaying techniques (using a dual slot belay device and climbing rope)    provided by our trained staff. By the end of the course, participants will be    able to overcome more challenging routes and feel comfortable climbing with    friends! Harnesses provided. Participants must be within 40 - 300 lbs. and    must wear closed toed shoes.

An Introduction to skateboarding. Learn the basics of skateboarding from balance, pushing, turning and cruising on low impact ramps and surfaces. We offer a safe place for beginning skateboarders to learn how to stand on a skateboard properly while maintaining our balance. We will cover the safety aspects and “flow” of skating flat ground obstacles/ramps. We’ll also assist in basic skateboard maintenance and identify each part of the skateboard. Our instructors are trained and experienced in teaching youth and helping kids and adults navigate their way through the fundamentals of skateboarding. Helmets are mandatory. We will provide helmets and skateboards if needed.

This    after school jewelry class is offered for those interested in taking their    metal arts skills to the next level. Both beginning and intermediate level    students are welcome. Beginning students will be introduced to the basic    skills of professional jewelry making and metalsmithing, and returning    students will dive deeper into techniques to create unique pieces such as    pendants, earrings and rings as well as 3-D objects made of copper and brass.    Intermediate students will be given the opportunity to work with sterling    silver. Materials are included in the price of the class. The Jewelry Studio    is located on the upper floor, with stair access only. For accommodations    requests or accessibility questions, please contact rpdaccess@sfgov.org or    415-831-6841. Please note that submitting your request at least two weeks    before the beginning of the class will help ensure availability.

event_name: First Steps Portola (Playgroup, English, Spanish, Cantonese, Vietnamese)
event_description: Build healthy bonding and enjoy fun activities together, while learning about your child’s cognitive and emotional development. Activities include arts, movement, songs, and stories. For ages 6 – 36 months + parents/caregivers. Free to enroll! Please note: due to our small class size, we ask families to register only for the classes you are able to attend. If you are no longer able to attend a class, please cancel your registration or contact us at firststeps@fccenters.org. Thank you! Registration will open at 9:00 am on the 28th of each month.   ·Portola: Mondays and Wednesdays, 9:00-10:30 am · Excelsior: Tuesdays and Thursdays, 9:00-10:30 am · Visitacion Valley: Thursdays, 9:30-11:00 am. (18-36 months + caregiver) For more information or to join, contact Elsa at 415.715.6746 or firststeps@fccenters.org • • • Primeros Pasos (First Steps) es un espacio para que las familias aprendan juntas. Las maestras lo guiarán a usted y a sus pequeños a través de actividades que incluyen canciones, bailes, y lecturas divertidas. Para edades de 6–36 meses + cuidador/a. Gratis para inscribirse. Tenga en cuenta: debido a nuestro pequeño tamaño de clase, le pedimos a las familias que se registren solo para las clases a las que puede asistir. Si ya no puede asistir a una clase, cancele su registro o contáctenos en firststeps@fccenters.org. ¡Gracias! Las inscripciones se abrirán el día 28 de cada mes a las 9 de la mañana. • • • First Steps是適合孩子和家長一起學習的遊戲小組。 我們的老師將與您們一起歌曲、舞蹈、閲讀等活動。 免費報名。適合6-36個月的孩子 + 家長/監護人。 請注意：由於我們的班級規模較小，我們要求家庭只註冊您可以參加的課程。 如果您不能再上課，請取消註冊或通過 firststeps@fccenters.org 聯繫我們。 謝謝你! 每月28日上午9:00開始報名。 • • • First Steps là một nhóm trẻ mẫu giáo được giám sát bởi người lớn để các gia đình học tập cùng nhau. Các giáo viên của chúng tôi sẽ hướng dẫn bạn và con bạn thông qua các hoạt động hấp dẫn liên quan đến bài hát, điệu nhảy ngộ nghĩnh. Từ 6-36 tháng tuổi + cha mẹ/người chăm sóc. Ghi danh miễn phí. Xin lưu ý: do quy mô lớp học nhỏ, chúng tôi yêu cầu các gia đình chỉ đăng ký cho các lớp học mà bạn có thể tham dự. Nếu bạn không thể tham gia lớp học được nữa, vui lòng hủy đăng ký hoặc liên hệ với chúng tôi tại firststeps@fccenters.org. Cảm ơn! Cổng đăng ký sẽ mở vào lúc 9:00 sáng ngày 28 hàng tháng.

Pedal    alongside San Francisco’s iconic waterfront on this scenic, guided bayfront    ride! We’ll cruise the Embarcadero with unbeatable views of the Bay Bridge,    sail past Pier 39’s lively harbor, and roll through the historic curve of    Aquatic Park. This ride blends smooth waterfront paths with classic city    scenery for a truly unforgettable outing. Riders should bring their own bike,    helmet, water, sunscreen, and a light snack. We’ll start with a quick safety    refresher and route overview before setting off. Designed for riders with    some experience, this tour includes steady-paced riding with occasional    street crossings.

This class introduces hand building techniques including pinch, coil, and slab construction, and basic wheel throwing techniques of wedging, centering, throwing cups and bowls, and trimming. Instructor provides individual guidance for all skill levels. Surface decoration and glazing techniques will also be explored. Clay is available for purchase at the studio with a 100-pound clay limit per session. No outside clay or glazes allowed. Students must purchase a basic pottery tool kit prior to the first day of class. Suggested materials list can be found at sharonartstudio.org. Students may enroll in only one ceramics class per session. Note: New students (new to ceramics or Sharon Art Studio) must attend the first three classes. All skill levels welcome.

event_name: Jewelry Workshop: Basics of Custom Prong Setting
event_description: Take    your jewelry-making to the next level by learning to make a prong setting!    Students will expand upon their metalsmithing skills by learning how to craft    custom prongs, solder, and polish a sterling silver setting. Our wonderful    jewelry studio is outfitted with all the tools and equipment to take your    jewelry making to the next level and beyond. Students must have taken the    beginner course previously or demonstrate equivalent skills. Class fee    includes the use of tools and materials for one sterling silver prong    setting. Students who wish to use materials beyond what is provided need to    have the approval of the instructor and be responsible for purchasing and    safe storage. Additional silver and gemstones can be purchased in class for a    fee, payable to the instructor. Jewelry making requires normal hand    dexterity. Students must attend class on time to receive instruction that    will not be repeated. Tools and materials available. The Jewelry Studio is    located on the upper floor, with stair access only. For accommodations    requests or accessibility questions, please contact rpdaccess@sfgov.org or    415-831-6841. Please note that submitting your request at least two weeks    before the beginning of the class will help ensure availability.

This    class introduces advanced skills of acrylic painting. From image transfer,    color theory, textures, and detail techniques. Come explore working with    different acrylic mediums. This class will be explored through direct    observation of still-life flowers, ferns, plants, and photos of landscapes or    animals. Please bring requested materials to class. Materials list available    at sharonartstudio.org.

event_name: Drawing with Soft Pastels: Portrait & Figure
event_description: Come explore working with soft pastels to create portraits and figuredrawings. In this class we will go over basic pastel fundamentals, how touse and mix colors, and how to create your own paper surface for bothportrait and figure. Develop images from gesture poses, short poses,ending with 2 hours poses. Beginners welcome. Cost of the model includedin the price of the class. Please bring requested materials to class, Materials list available at sharonartstudio.org.

event_name: Oil Painting Workshop: Trees of San Francisco
event_description: In this workshop, students will learn how to paint with oil in a non-toxic/sustainable way, while gaining a newappreciation for the trees in San Francisco - who will be serving as our muse for the class activity. We’ll do anoverview of oil paints as a medium, their history, and a quick overview of color theory. Then diving right in,students will be guided on how to use paint brushes and a palette knife to create their own unique version of a treeof San Francisco (provided by the teacher). This workshop is perfect for both beginners and intermediate artists who want to learn the basics of oil painting, sharpen their eye for detail, all while focusing on one of the magnificent trees of San Francisco. By the end of the workshop, students will have a new set of oil painting skills and the proof to show for it! Their ready to frame piece of art will make for a great gift or home decor addition! 8x10 canvas, palettes, palette knives, and cleaning materials provided. Students will be required to bring paint set and brushes, and be encouraged to bring an apron or wear clothes to get messy in. Please see materials list for what is required to bring to the workshop. Materials list available at sharonartstudio.org.

Basic  metal working knowledge is required to take this class. Learn the ins and  outs of using a hydraulic press to shape and form metal, texturing with a  rolling mill, and more while exploring the world of metal arts. Students will  learn various stone settings, die forming using a hydraulic press, acid  etching, and more. The cost of the class includes the use of tools and access  to basic materials. Students are responsible for purchasing materials  specific to desired projects. Intermediate and advanced level students are  welcome. The Jewelry Studio is located on the upper floor, with stair access  only. For accommodations requests or accessibility questions, please contact  rpdaccess@sfgov.org or 415-831-6841. Please note that submitting your request  at least two weeks before the beginning of the class will help ensure  availability.

Let    the art adventures begin early! This playful, hands-on class is designed    especially for our youngest artists. Together, children and their caregivers    will use toys and familiar art tools to make this introduction to art extra    fun. Painting with sponges, miniature cars, rollers and fingers all add to    the hands-on experience and keep little hands and minds engaged. Our young    artists will also have the chance to explore alternative activities that    encourage social interaction and fine motor skills throughout each class.    Participating toddlers must be accompanied by a participating adult. As with    every art class, dress for a mess! Appropriate for toddlers 2 to 4 years,    accompanied by a participating adult.

This is    a required course for all potential members of the Photography Center. This    course is not required if you just want to take a photography class. This    course will include a talk about the rules and regulations of the Photography    Center, a complete tour of the facility including a tour of our forty    enlarger darkroom with instructions on the uses for the enlargers and how to    process both your resin coated and fiber black and white prints for optimum    results. You will see the film developing rooms and learn about the uses of    the drymount presses. You will also visit the Gallery plus the Digital Lab.    After the tour, there will be a question and answer session to address any of    the subjects regarding black and white photography. Call the Photo Center for    more information at 415-554-9522.

This class is designed to orient participants to the aquatic environment and to help them gain basic aquatic skills. In addition, participants start learning about how to be safe around water. Children must be 48 to participate.          Registration is limited to one class per participant.

Welcome to our 25th Annual SFRPD All-City Jr. Warriors Youth Basketball League in San Francisco! Our Jr. Warriors League depends on the generosity of volunteers to provide an opportunity for our youth (Kindergarten - 8th Grade) to learn the game of basketball in a recreational, supportive, and safe environment. Each team will have league games (6 or more) and weekly practices. Jr. Warriors League games will be played on Thursdays, Fridays, or Saturdays at different Recreation Centers depending on grade level. If you are interested in becoming a coach/assistant coach, referee, or scorekeeper, you do not need to have a high level of experience in basketball. Our league offers an annual coaching clinic and experienced coaches who are more than happy to provide advice.

This class should improve participants' proficiency in performing the swimming strokes that were introduced in Level 3. Participants perform these strokes with increased proficiency and can swim them for greater distances. In addition, participants learn the arm actions that accompany the scissors kick and breaststroke kick to begin performing the sidestroke and breaststroke at rudimentary proficiency levels. Participants also learn the back crawl and butterfly at rudimentary proficiency levels, in addition to the basics of performing a simple open turn at a wall. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 3.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

Discover the creative possibilities of gelli plate printing in this hands-on workshop designed for adult learners of all experience levels. Students will learn the basics of gelli printing, including how to prep the gelli plate, how to ink it, how to create designs that can be easily printed, and how to make stellar prints. We will begin with focused instruction in design and color specific to gelli printing, helping you understand how layering, contrast, and transparency work in this unique process. Moving forward, students will create images that work in a positive/negative style on their gelli plates, exploring how shapes, textures, and stencils interact to produce dynamic, one-of-a-kind prints. Participants will leave with a collection of original prints and a deeper understanding of this playful and versatile printmaking technique.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). event_name: First Steps Portola (Playgroup, English, Spanish, Cantonese, Vietnamese)
event_description: Build healthy bonding and enjoy fun activities together, while learning about your child’s cognitive and emotional development. Activities include arts, movement, songs, and stories. For ages 6 – 36 months + parents/caregivers. Free to enroll! Please note: due to our small class size, we ask families to register only for the classes you are able to attend. If you are no longer able to attend a class, please cancel your registration or contact us at firststeps@fccenters.org. Thank you! Registration will open at 9:00 am on the 28th of each month.   ·Portola: Mondays and Wednesdays, 9:00-10:30 am · Excelsior: Tuesdays and Thursdays, 9:00-10:30 am · Visitacion Valley: Thursdays, 9:30-11:00 am. (18-36 months + caregiver) For more information or to join, contact Elsa at 415.715.6746 or firststeps@fccenters.org • • • Primeros Pasos (First Steps) es un espacio para que las familias aprendan juntas. Las maestras lo guiarán a usted y a sus pequeños a través de actividades que incluyen canciones, bailes, y lecturas divertidas. Para edades de 6–36 meses + cuidador/a. Gratis para inscribirse. Tenga en cuenta: debido a nuestro pequeño tamaño de clase, le pedimos a las familias que se registren solo para las clases a las que puede asistir. Si ya no puede asistir a una clase, cancele su registro o contáctenos en firststeps@fccenters.org. ¡Gracias! Las inscripciones se abrirán el día 28 de cada mes a las 9 de la mañana. • • • First Steps是適合孩子和家長一起學習的遊戲小組。 我們的老師將與您們一起歌曲、舞蹈、閲讀等活動。 免費報名。適合6-36個月的孩子 + 家長/監護人。 請注意：由於我們的班級規模較小，我們要求家庭只註冊您可以參加的課程。 如果您不能再上課，請取消註冊或通過 firststeps@fccenters.org 聯繫我們。 謝謝你! 每月28日上午9:00開始報名。 • • • First Steps là một nhóm trẻ mẫu giáo được giám sát bởi người lớn để các gia đình học tập cùng nhau. Các giáo viên của chúng tôi sẽ hướng dẫn bạn và con bạn thông qua các hoạt động hấp dẫn liên quan đến bài hát, điệu nhảy ngộ nghĩnh. Từ 6-36 tháng tuổi + cha mẹ/người chăm sóc. Ghi danh miễn phí. Xin lưu ý: do quy mô lớp học nhỏ, chúng tôi yêu cầu các gia đình chỉ đăng ký cho các lớp học mà bạn có thể tham dự. Nếu bạn không thể tham gia lớp học được nữa, vui lòng hủy đăng ký hoặc liên hệ với chúng tôi tại firststeps@fccenters.org. Cảm ơn! Cổng đăng ký sẽ mở vào lúc 9:00 sáng ngày 28 hàng tháng.

Our league offers an annual coaching clinic and experienced coaches who are more than happy to provide advice.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

Discover the serene beauty of San Francisco’s waterways with a self-guided kayaking experience at either Lake Merced or China Basin. Paddle at your own pace as you explore the lake’s tranquil waters, diverse wildlife, and natural habitats—an ideal way to connect with nature and enjoy a refreshing outdoor adventure right in the city. Enrollment includes the rental of a tandem (two-person) kayak and covers up to two participants. Personal flotation devices are provided for all participants. Children 12 and under must be accompanied by an adult in the kayak. All participants must sign a release waiver on the day of their session. Instructional safety videos must be viewed prior to paddling; a link to the videos and waiver will be emailed the week before your scheduled time. Registered participants under the age of 12 must be accompanied on the water by a registered parent or guardian. Expect to get wet—please bring a towel and a change of clothes.

event_name: First Steps Visitacion Valley (Playgroup, English, Spanish, Cantonese, Vietnamese)
event_description: Build healthy bonding and enjoy fun activities together, while learning about your child’s cognitive and emotional development. Activities include arts, movement, songs, and stories. For ages 18 – 36 months + parents/caregivers. Free to enroll! Please note: due to our small class size, we ask families to register only for the classes you are able to attend. If you are no longer able to attend a class, please cancel your registration or contact us at firststeps@fccenters.org. Thank you! Registration will open at 9:00 am on the 28th of each month. · Visitacion Valley: Thursdays, 9:30-11:00 am. (18-36 months + caregiver) For more information or to join, contact Elsa at 415.715.6746 or firststeps@fccenters.org • • • Primeros Pasos (First Steps) es un espacio para que las familias aprendan juntas. Las maestras lo guiarán a usted y a sus pequeños a través de actividades que incluyen canciones, bailes, y lecturas divertidas. Para edades de 6–36 meses + cuidador/a. Gratis para inscribirse. Tenga en cuenta: debido a nuestro pequeño tamaño de clase, le pedimos a las familias que se registren solo para las clases a las que puede asistir. Si ya no puede asistir a una clase, cancele su registro o contáctenos en firststeps@fccenters.org. ¡Gracias! Las inscripciones se abrirán el día 28 de cada mes a las 9 de la mañana. • • • First Steps是適合孩子和家長一起學習的遊戲小組。 我們的老師將與您們一起歌曲、舞蹈、閲讀等活動。 免費報名。適合6-36個月的孩子 + 家長/監護人。 請注意：由於我們的班級規模較小，我們要求家庭只註冊您可以參加的課程。 如果您不能再上課，請取消註冊或通過 firststeps@fccenters.org 聯繫我們。 謝謝你! 每月28日上午9:00開始報名。 • • • First Steps là một nhóm trẻ mẫu giáo được giám sát bởi người lớn để các gia đình học tập cùng nhau. Các giáo viên của chúng tôi sẽ hướng dẫn bạn và con bạn thông qua các hoạt động hấp dẫn liên quan đến bài hát, điệu nhảy ngộ nghĩnh. Từ 6-36 tháng tuổi + cha mẹ/người chăm sóc. Ghi danh miễn phí. Xin lưu ý: do quy mô lớp học nhỏ, chúng tôi yêu cầu các gia đình chỉ đăng ký cho các lớp học mà bạn có thể tham dự. Nếu bạn không thể tham gia lớp học được nữa, vui lòng hủy đăng ký hoặc liên hệ với chúng tôi tại firststeps@fccenters.org. Cảm ơn! Cổng đăng ký sẽ mở vào lúc 9:00 sáng ngày 28 hàng tháng.

Knotting    isn’t just for pearls, it’s a way to keep precious gemstone beads evenly    spaced, prevent wear at the edges, and save the beads from scattering if the    thread is broken. Try this ancient technique for yourself! This class will    discuss the differences between thread material and types of gemstones.    You’ll learn how to properly thread precious gemstones, including pearls,    into a necklace or bracelet. You’ll have access to a variety of different    types of clasps, thread, and gemstones so you can truly create a    one-of-a-kind piece of wearable art! Tools and materials available. Light    refreshments provided to quench your thirst as you work.

In  this creative and dynamic class we will explore printmaking with soft pastel,  watercolor, and acrylic painting opens up so many possibilities for artistic  expression. Each medium brings its own unique qualities to the artwork, and  when combined, they can create stunning textures, layers, and visual effects.  Participants will have the opportunity to experiment with different  techniques and materials, allowing for a truly multidimensional approach to  their artwork. It's a fantastic opportunity for artists to push their  boundaries and explore new ways of working with mixed media. Please bring  supplies to class. Materials list available at sharonartstudio.org.

Join    The Call of the Sea, St. Francis Yacht Club, and other youth,      in a three-hour voyage on Seaward, an 82-foot ship. All youth      will become sailors and scientists for the day. You will get to      help sail the ship. You will also get to learn about ecology,      marine life, sailing skills and teamwork. Seaward will do a lap      of the bay. You will board at the docks of the St. Francis Yacht      Club. The route will begin with a ride to the Golden Gate Bridge,      a view from below the bridge and then will go around Angel      Island, near Alcatraz and then, on the way back to the yacht      club, you will sail past city landmarks along the waterfront.      Every participant should bring non- skid shoes such as tennis      shoes, long pants, a jacket and layers of clothes. The Saint      Francis Yacht Club will only be a pick up/drop off point for this      class. There is no waiting area for parents or guardians. The      address is 99 Yacht Rd, San Francisco, CA 94123. This event will      go on rain or shine. Questions please contact Rex.Biteng@sfgov.      org **EACH CHILD MAY SIGN UP FOR ONLY ONE SESSION.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

Discover    the colorful, creative world of polymer clay jewelry!      In this hands-on class, instructor Sophie Wertz will guide you through the    process of designing and creating your own unique sets of earrings. Polymer    clay has become a favorite medium among DIY jewelry makers — it’s    lightweight, vibrant, and incredibly versatile. Once you learn a few key    sculpting techniques, the design possibilities are endless! You’ll start by    getting familiar with polymer clay through short lessons on color mixing,    clay conditioning, and handling techniques. Sophie will demonstrate popular    methods like marbling, sculpting miniature florals, and using carving and    modeling tools. You’ll have access to a variety of cutters, rollers, and    texture tools to shape and personalize your designs. From there, you’ll learn    how to prepare clay sheets, bake your creations, assemble, and finish your    earrings. By the end of class, you’ll go home with a custom jewelry piece and    leave with confidence, skills, and know-how to keep creating polymer clay    jewelry on your own! Tools and materials provided.

This class introduces hand building techniques including pinch, coil, and slab construction, and basic wheel throwing techniques of wedging, centering, throwing cups and bowls, and trimming. Instructor provides individual guidance for all skill levels. Surface decoration and glazing techniques will also be explored. Clay is available for purchase at the studio with a 100-pound clay limit per session. No outside clay or glazes allowed. Students must purchase a basic pottery tool kit prior to the first day of class. Suggested materials list can be found at sharonartstudio.org. Students may enroll in only one ceramics class per session. Note: New students (new to ceramics or Sharon Art Studio) must attend the first three classes. All skill levels welcome.

event_name: Advanced Figure Drawing: Space to Play
event_description: Please  note: this is an advanced level figure drawing class. Drawing experience  required. Figure drawing is an active process; an engagement with material  that is both physical and intellectual. In this class, students will be  encouraged to work in terms of process rather than making a finished product,  in order to foster curiosity and therefore, insight. Insights will be learned  through visual problem solving, exploring the looking and seeing  relationship, and the expression of touching marker to paper. This class is a  choose your own adventure, as it is completely self-directed. As soon as  class starts, we will dive into meditation as a group through deep  concentrated drawing time. Emphasis will be on gesture poses, working our way  up through short poses of various time lengths, and ending each class with 20  minute poses. In addition, our entire final class day will be spent on a long  pose. (Troubleshooting, corrections, and critiques of student work made upon  request to the instructor during 5 minute breaks between poses.) Price of the  model is included in the cost of the class. The cost includes a $115 model  fee. Please bring paper and drawing materials to class. Materials list  available at sharonartstudio.org.

event_name: Jewelry Workshop: Intro to Jewelry Design & Hand Sawing
event_description: Transform  your graphic drawings into stunning metal jewelry and art pieces using  fundamental metalsmithing techniques. This accessible course focuses on hand  sawing and piercing sheet metal to create dynamic components with minimal  tools. Students will explore the interplay of positive and negative space  while mastering essential hand sawing skills that form the foundation of  metalsmithing. Students can choose one or more depending on their ambition  level such as earrings, pendants, decorative window hangings, or brooches.  This course emphasizes creativity and personal expression through  metal--perfect for beginners and those looking to strengthen their  fundamental hand sawing skills. All tools and materials provided.

event_name: Drawing at the de Young Museum
event_description: This hands-on workshop invites participants to explore the rich, tactile world of oil pastels through a series of guided exercises inspired by the vibrant collections of the de Young Museum. Blending drawing and painting techniques, participants will learn how to layer, blend, and build texture using oil pastels to create expressive, colorful works on paper. Participants will engage with museum artworks as sources of inspiration—drawing connections between historical and contemporary uses of color, composition, and gesture. Emphasis will be placed on personal expression, process, and experimentation rather than representational accuracy, making this workshop accessible to all skill levels.At the de Young Museum, sketching is allowed in the permanent collection with a pencil and a small (9 x 12 inch or smaller) pad. At the first class the class will meet at the lily pound outside of the de Young. Please do not be late for the first day of the class as important information and rules will be covered before going inside the museum. Students are responsible for their own entry tickets if needed. Please bring drawing materials to class. See materials list at sharonartstudio.org.

Each    week, a different animal is the star of our classroom. We learn fun facts and    explore the wonders of these amazing animals. In    this beginner class, each student can expect to design and fabricate a unique    sterling silver stone set ring. Students will learn foundational    silversmithing techniques- cut metal with the jewelers saw, sand, file,    stamp, form, solder and create a bezel cup in order to fabricate their final    product. Materials and tools are provided with the cost of the class, but please feel    free to bring your own cabochons and supplies. If this will be your first    ring and you would like to purchase your own cabochons to use in the class,    please purchase oval or circular. Perfect    for beginners and returning makers, this class invites creativity,    exploration, and a love of imperfect, organic beauty. Tools and clay    provided.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

Registered participants under the age of 12 must be accompanied on the water by a registered parent or guardian. Expect to get wet—please bring a towel and a change of clothes.

Our after school program is an experience that provides a safe and nurturing environment for youth in grades K-5 to develop life long recreation and leisure skills. Participants will receive homework assistance, be exposed to an environment that will promote literacy, encourage communication and empowerment skills while providing recreation activities that include sports, group games, arts and culture, community exploration and seasonal special events. All staff and volunteers receive background checks and are trained in safety skills. Start times may vary based on the school release time. The fee for the school year is $1,080. Parents will have the option to pay the entire fee upon registration. Payment plans are available. $270 is due upon registration and on the first day of October, January and March of the school year.

Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 4.

event_description: Swim Academy is a new pilot program for first-time swimmers who have never taken a Level 1 swim class. Students will start in Level 1 and have the opportunity to progress through Level 3 as they develop their skills. To move to the next level, swimmers must successfully pass the required exit skills. Enrollment in the next level is only offered in the following session, and only to those who meet the exit criteria—no exceptions. If a child does not pass their current level, they will not continue in the Academy at this time.

Welcome to our 25th Annual SFRPD All-City Jr. Warriors Youth Basketball League in San Francisco! Our Jr. Warriors League depends on the generosity of volunteers to provide an opportunity for our youth (Kindergarten - 8th Grade) to learn the game of basketball in a recreational, supportive, and safe environment. Each team will have league games (6 or more) and weekly practices. Jr. Warriors League games will be played on Thursdays, Fridays, or Saturdays at different Recreation Centers depending on grade level. If you are interested in becoming a coach/assistant coach, referee, or scorekeeper, you do not need to have a high level of experience in basketball. Our league offers an annual coaching clinic and experienced coaches who are more than happy to provide advice.

Each    week, a different animal is the star of our classroom. We learn fun facts and    explore the wonders of these amazing animals. Often, a live animal pays us a    visit in person; other times we closely examine skeletons, taxidermy models,    and habitats. Then we get busy making art inspired by their unique    characteristics. You can count on having fun, getting messy and learning    something new every week. Class fee includes one child and one participating    adult. Please register using the child's name.

This    course will be taught by former University of San Francisco tennis team    standout – David Hong. This class will teach players how to rally, be    familiar with singles/doubles formats, keep score, & be able to play a    match with United States Tennis Association rules & regulations. Coach    Hong will work on advanced tournament style drills & match play. This is    not a beginners tennis course & is for the advanced player.

This level continues to focus on building more comfort and enjoyment in the water using songs, games and play. While introducing more structured play in the areas of bobbing, breath control, floating, gliding and kicking on front and back, in addition to arm rotations and other elementary skills. Children ages 3 and under are required to wear swim diapers while in the pool. The ratio is 1 adult per child. Swim classes are limited to one class per person per session.

event_description: Join us    for a hands-on introduction to sewing in this beginner-friendly class. You'll    learn essential sewing machine skills including how to thread a machine, wind    bobbins, cut fabric, and troubleshoot basic issues. Practice key techniques    like straight stitching, box corners, hemming, and using a simple pattern.    All materials provided.
site_location_name: HARVEY MILK CENTER FOR THE ARTS

event_description: This class is a non-contact training experience designed to develop    and refine essential boxing skills through consistent repetition and    high-energy drills. Focused on mastering real, time-tested boxing    fundamentals, this class builds a strong foundation—no gimmicks, no flashy    moves, just authentic technique. Perfect for beginners and seasoned    enthusiasts alike, it emphasizes footwork, form, and conditioning in a safe,    supportive, and non-contact environment.

Step into your future with Pathways & Possibilities - a creative and empowering workshop designed just for teens. Through the art of vision boarding, participants will explore their goals, passions, and dreams, transforming them into vibrant visual representations. Whether you're dreaming big or just figuring things out, this hands-on experience will help you clarify your path, boost your confidence, and connect with others who are on their own journeys. Let your imagination lead the way!

Explore the vast, imaginative possibilities of clay in the Randall's open studio setting. Hone your skills throwing on a wheel or hand-building, making something for use or building sculptural pieces. If you have some experience in clay, whether back in high school or recently, and would like to develop a project and take your skills to the next level, this class is for you. Get one-on-one guidance and support from our experienced instructors.

Learn to    create beautiful floral arrangements for everyday use, gifting, entertaining    and special occasions. Students may    enroll in only one ceramics class per session. Note: New students (new to    ceramics or Sharon Art Studio) must attend the first three classes. All skill    levels welcome.

Come  experience life drawing! Each class begins with gesture drawing warm ups  followed by progressively longer poses. The final class will be a single  pose. Our subject is the human form. The long pose is an invitation to  develop a drawn study or a finished work in a medium of your choosing.  Materials and techniques discussed. No fume producing materials please  (turpentines, spray fixatives indoors, etc.). On-the-spot instruction  provided. Music played during class. Class finishes in a mini show with reflection  and friendly feedback. Please bring a sketchbook and preferred drawing  materials to class. Various drawing materials will also be provided. The cost  includes a $100 model fee.

A perfect place to start if it’s your first time stepping on a skateboard. We offer a safe place for beginning skateboarders to learn how to stand on a skateboard properly while maintaining our balance. Our instructors are trained and experienced in teaching Tot skateboarders the very basics skating. We provide very low impact ramps designed for beginner skaters. Helmets are mandatory.  Skateboards and helmets will be provided if needed. Each child must be accompanied by participating adult.

There is much more in Hatha yoga practice than poses. In this series, we still explore practices aimed to improve our physical well-being through asanas (poses); we also introduce practices that include pranayama (breath expansion) techniques, and finally we experience the benefits of simple meditation techniques. The intention is awareness at a physical, mental and emotional level on as well as off the mat.

event_name: New Technologies: Electronic Inventor Lab with AI Coding
event_description: What if    you could invent the machine to feed your dog when it's hungry, or the    clothing that lights up to the rhythms of your heart beat? In this hands-on    course we’ll use AI to do the coding while we focus on learning to use    programmable microcontrollers (Arduinos) to interface with the physical world    through sensors, animating LED displays, motors, and more. Moving from group    projects to individual inventions, you will learn the principles and theory    of practical electronics and circuit building, as well as best practices for    creating AI generated code that can enable your creative power. Learn how to    get your ideas and inventions out of your head and into existence. No    experience is required. Basic electronics supplies are provided for the    class, but there’s an additional material fee of $40. A paid subscription to    an AI service such as ChatGPT or Gemini is recommended. Repeat students are    welcomed and can work on their ongoing projects. This class pairs well with a    Digital Fab Lab course that focuses on building and fabrication.

The    Feldenkrais method is an educational system that allows the body to move and    function more efficiently and comfortably. Its goal is to re-educate the    nervous system and improve motor ability.

Mindstorm Robot kits and    laptops are provided for class use. Due to the progressive learning format,    students who miss more than one class with instructor permission may be    dropped without refund.

Playful    Intuitive Art Exploration is a fun and exploratory drawing and painting class    that gives folks an opportunity to express themselves creatively through    creating art and connecting with their intuition. We will be taking    inspiration from unique real-world images (centered around nature and    microscopic photography) which incorporate interesting colors, textures, and    shapes. You will learn basic drawing techniques using the elements of art and    will be experimenting with abstract and representational concepts using your    intuition as a guide. You get to be the orchestrator here. There is no right    or wrong in this class and no prior drawing experience is necessary! Join us    and have some fun!

This    class is a playful, low-pressure dive into abstract image-making through hand    printed techniques. We’ll focus on core visual principles: texture,    repetition, color, and composition while creating intuitive, expressive    prints using linoleum blocks, gelatin plates, and collage. event_name: Lifeguard Training Class with Oxygen Administration
event_description: The primary purpose of the lifeguard training program is to provide entry level lifeguard skills and knowledge to prevent, recognize, and respond to emergencies and to provide care for sudden illnesses until advanced medical personnel arrives and takes over. This program includes a lifeguard training course with aquatics specific first aid and cardio-pulmonary resuscitation (CPR) training. NOTE: Participants MUST pass the pre-test on the first day of class. The test consists of the following: 300-yard swim; tread water for 2 minutes without the use of arms; swim 20 yards, then surface dive to retrieve a 10-lb. brick, swim back to the starting point with both hands on the brick, and climb out of the water without assistance, skill must be performed in under 1minute 40 seconds. Depending on the skills of the participants and their comprehension of the materials presented, the participants may be dismissed early or need to stay later each day.

event_name: Tennis - Vocabulary, Chess & Art Spring Break Camp
event_description: The Maunupau    Method-Learning & Fun Tennis System is an eclectic mix of tennis    instruction methodologies from; SFRPD, USTA, USPTA, PTR, & the MM-LAFTS    certification curriculum, as well as 30+ years of on court coaching in the    public & private sector. Instruction is divided into; safety &    technical lecture, drills to support the theme of the technical lecture, fun    games that are related to the theme of the technical lecture, & match    play. Campers will learn the etymology of tennis grips; continental, eastern    forehand, semi-western, full western, & eastern 1 handed backhand.    Students will also learn stances; square, open, & closed, as well as    pronation on the serve. Campers will also be introduced to the game of chess,    a tennis themed art project, & a word of the day, to increase high school    vocabulary.

Drawing  With Dynamic Value  In this class you will  develop a dynamic, value-based approach to drawing that can strengthen both  technical skill and creative expression. Learn the principles of shading and  how to apply them in drawings from life or imagination. We’ll explore how to  “paint” with powdered charcoal, use blending stumps for smooth transitions,  simplify complex scenes through reductive value, and work effectively on  toned paper. You’ll also investigate value using both charcoal and graphite,  gaining confidence in tools and techniques that bring form and depth to your  work. This class is open to all skill levels—whether you’re new to shading or  already comfortable with value but looking to expand your practice. A $138  model fee is included in the price of the class. Please bring requested  materials to class. Materials list available at sharonartstudio.org.

Drawing Practice with Meditation welcomes participants to a focused space for observational drawing practice beginning with a 5 minute silent meditation. Subjects include a mix of figure and still life. Materials covered: graphite, charcoal, ink. Tools and techniques presented: gesture, contour, sighting, measuring, value scale, composition, viewfinder, scaling, thumbnails. The session wraps with a mini-show to reflect on the work and share friendly feedback. Newsprint, paper and some supplies are provided. Please bring requested materials to class. Materials list available at sharonartstudio.org. The cost of the class includes the cost of the model.

Advanced students: No grinding the      first 2 hours of the first class. Note: Students may enroll in only one    glass class per session. No glass fusing allowed during this class.

Come to a  place where we build Deaf community, language and culture. The    Deaf Club will be meeting once a month on the first Friday of each month    during the season. This space provides time for Deaf community members and their    families, as well as anyone interested in engaging in Deaf culture and    developing American Sign Language skills.  The first    half of the evening is designed to support those learning American Sign    Language (ASL), including ASL students, and parents who have a child who is    Deaf or hard of hearing.  The second half of the evening is focused on    providing a space for members of the Deaf community, to share culture,    resources and socialize in a sign language-only environment.  Anyone is    welcome to stay for the second half of the evening; but they should be    prepared to hold their own in conversation.  This is a drop-in program,    but a Recreation and Parks Play Pass or sign-in is required.

This class should improve participants' proficiency in performing the swimming strokes that were introduced in Level 3. Participants perform these strokes with increased proficiency and can swim them for greater distances. This class is designed to help participants gain basic aquatic skills and swimming strokes, including the front crawl, breaststroke and elementary backstroke. This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

Learn  the organic metal art of lost wax casting. This course will cover the process  by which metal object is cast from a wax model, allowing you to see the  limitless forms that metal can take. The class starts by showing you how to  work with wax (hot and cold) to create pieces of jewelry that will be cast.  The class fee covers the cost of basic materials. Each student will be given  one 2 1/2 inch flask to fit their wax designs in. Students are responsible  for purchasing sterling silver which will be covered in class. Instructor  will be doing the castings for the students. Beginners are welcome. The  Jewelry Studio is located on the upper floor, with stair access only. For  accommodations requests or accessibility questions, please contact  rpdaccess@sfgov.org or 415-831-6841. Please note that submitting your request  at least two weeks before the beginning of the class will help ensure  availability.

event_name: Jewelry Workshop: Intro to Up-Cycled Jewelry Design
event_description: Give life    back to your broken and outdated costume and broken jewelry. In this class,    students will design and craft unique up-cycled jewelry while learning    foundational metalsmithing skills such as jump rings, light soldering, hand    sawing, hammer techniques, wire forging, and more. Skills will depend on the    type of jewelry the student brings and the designs they wish to create. The    instructor will assist with design and fabrication strategy to keep the    expected results within the students' skill level. This is a beginner class,    and we will not be working with fine jewelry or metals. Tools and materials    provided.

This    class introduces hand building techniques including pinch, coil, and slab    construction, and basic wheel throwing techniques of wedging, centering,    throwing cups and bowls, and trimming. Instructor provides individual    guidance for all skill levels. Surface decoration and glazing techniques will    also be explored. Clay is available for purchase at the studio with a    100-pound clay limit per session. No outside clay or glazes allowed. Students    must purchase a basic pottery tool kit prior to the first day of class.    Suggested materials list can be found at sharonartstudio.org. Students may    enroll in only one ceramics class per session. Note: New students (new to    ceramics or Sharon Art Studio) must attend the first three classes. All skill    levels welcome.
Drop-In  Table Tennis is designed for players to work on their skills & meet new  opponents for a match. We have 3 tables available, bring your own paddles or  borrow ours.

Play-based    art exploration for toddlers and their caregivers. This class gives young    children opportunities to experience and experiment with all sorts of    materials, mediums and squishy things. Kids and caregivers are encouraged to    enjoy the process of manipulating everyday items into art. Dress for a mess!    Class fee includes one child and one participating adult. Please register    using the child's name.

Explore    the myriad of sculptural potential in clay. We will cover basic ceramic hand-    building, wheel thrown forms, surface decorations and glazing. Instructor    will work with advanced students to explore and develop individual techniques    and projects. All levels welcome.

event_name: The Elements of Art: Drawing & Painting with Tweens
event_description: Come    explore the elements of art through drawing and painting in this fun,    one-of-a-kind art class! Here we will experiment with foundational elements    of art such as line, shape, value, and form while taking visual information    and inspiration from striking images. On our journey we will play with    imagery from nature, objects from everyday life, and cartoon-inspired    art--while creating unique representational and abstract artwork. This class    aids in the development of visual art skills, which can deepen secondary    visual arts education.

(18-36 months + caregiver) For more information or to join, contact Elsa at 415.715.6746 or firststeps@fccenters.org • • • Primeros Pasos (First Steps) es un espacio para que las familias aprendan juntas. Las inscripciones se abrirán el día 28 de cada mes a las 9 de la mañana. • • • First Steps是適合孩子和家長一起學習的遊戲小組。 我們的老師將與您們一起歌曲、舞蹈、閲讀等活動。 免費報名。適合6-36個月的孩子 + 家長/監護人。 請注意：由於我們的班級規模較小，我們要求家庭只註冊您可以參加的課程。 如果您不能再上課，請取消註冊或通過 firststeps@fccenters.org 聯繫我們。 謝謝你! 每月28日上午9:00開始報名。 • • • First Steps là một nhóm trẻ mẫu giáo được giám sát bởi người lớn để các gia đình học tập cùng nhau. Các giáo viên của chúng tôi sẽ hướng dẫn bạn và con bạn thông qua các hoạt động hấp dẫn liên quan đến bài hát, điệu nhảy ngộ nghĩnh. Từ 6-36 tháng tuổi + cha mẹ/người chăm sóc. Ghi danh miễn phí. Nếu bạn không thể tham gia lớp học được nữa, vui lòng hủy đăng ký hoặc liên hệ với chúng tôi tại firststeps@fccenters.org. Cảm ơn! Cổng đăng ký sẽ mở vào lúc 9:00 sáng ngày 28 hàng tháng.

Pedal    alongside San Francisco’s iconic waterfront on this scenic, guided bayfront    ride! This ride blends smooth waterfront paths with classic city    scenery for a truly unforgettable outing. Riders should bring their own bike,    helmet, water, sunscreen, and a light snack. event_name: Mixed Media: Abstract and Figure-Hybrid Art
event_description: This    class emphasizes the power of inner vision—creating images from within,    rather than simply copying nature. While we will begin by studying and    imitating existing forms, the focus will shift toward transforming those    observations into original, expressive creations. The main goal of this    course is for students to discover their own unique visual style. By    exploring Surrealist, Cubist, and imitating ancient artistic influences,    students will experience the joy of creative transformation within oneself.      Students will first learn the principles of abstract geometric composition,    then move toward combining figurative or organic elements with abstraction.    The aim is to develop an individual artistic “flavor”—a step toward personal    originality.      Hands-on support will be provided throughout. No prior experience is    necessary. A $138 Model fee included in the price of the class. Please bring    supplies to class. Materials list available at sharonartstudio.org.

event_description: There is much more in Hatha yoga practice than poses. This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

event_name: New Technologies: Electronic Inventor Lab with AI Coding
event_description: What if    you could invent the machine to feed your dog when it's hungry, or the    clothing that lights up to the rhythms of your heart beat? In this hands-on    course we’ll use AI to do the coding while we focus on learning to use    programmable microcontrollers (Arduinos) to interface with the physical world    through sensors, animating LED displays, motors, and more. Moving from group    projects to individual inventions, you will learn the principles and theory    of practical electronics and circuit building, as well as best practices for    creating AI generated code that can enable your creative power. Learn how to    get your ideas and inventions out of your head and into existence. No    experience is required. Basic electronics supplies are provided for the    class, but there’s an additional material fee of $40. A paid subscription to    an AI service such as ChatGPT or Gemini is recommended. Repeat students are    welcomed and can work on their ongoing projects. This class pairs well with a    Digital Fab Lab course that focuses on building and fabrication.

During    this class students will learn how to make luminograms. Lumen prints are made    using gelatin silver paper, which is exposed to light and placed directly    into the fixer. The prints can be made using digital negatives or objects    (like a photogram), but they can also be made using only light itself.       Beautiful pastel tones emerge in the process, and the prints can be left    unfixed to further change over time. Students will experiment with different    techniques to better understand the factors that influence the colors of the    gelatin silver paper - the time of exposure, the type of light, and the kind    of paper used in the process.

event_description: Designed for two, discover the serene beauty of San Francisco’s waterways with a self-guided kayaking experience at either Lake Merced or China Basin. Paddle at your own pace as you explore the lake’s tranquil waters, diverse wildlife, and natural habitats; an ideal way to connect with nature and enjoy a refreshing outdoor adventure right in the city. Enrollment includes the rental of a tandem (two-person) kayak and covers up to two participants. Personal flotation devices are provided for all participants. Children 12 and under must be accompanied by an adult in the kayak. All participants must sign a release waiver on the day of their session. Instructional safety videos must be viewed prior to paddling; a link to the videos and waiver will be emailed the week before your scheduled time. Registered participants under the age of 12 must be accompanied on the water by a registered parent or guardian. Expect to get wet—please bring a towel and a change of clothes.

Join    The Call of the Sea, St. Francis Yacht Club, and other youth,      in a three-hour voyage on Seaward, an 82-foot ship. All youth      will become sailors and scientists for the day. You will get to      help sail the ship. You will also get to learn about ecology,      marine life, sailing skills and teamwork. Seaward will do a lap      of the bay. You will board at the docks of the St. Francis Yacht      Club. The route will begin with a ride to the Golden Gate Bridge,      a view from below the bridge and then will go around Angel      Island, near Alcatraz and then, on the way back to the yacht      club, you will sail past city landmarks along the waterfront.      Every participant should bring non- skid shoes such as tennis      shoes, long pants, a jacket and layers of clothes. The Saint      Francis Yacht Club will only be a pick up/drop off point for this      class. There is no waiting area for parents or guardians. The      address is 99 Yacht Rd, San Francisco, CA 94123. This event will      go on rain or shine. Questions please contact Rex.Biteng@sfgov.      org **EACH CHILD MAY SIGN UP FOR ONLY ONE SESSION.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

event_name: The Elements of Art: Drawing & Painting with Tweens
event_description: Come    explore the elements of art through drawing and painting in this fun,    one-of-a-kind art class! Here we will experiment with foundational elements    of art such as line, shape, value, and form while taking visual information    and inspiration from striking images. On our journey we will play with    imagery from nature, objects from everyday life, and cartoon-inspired    art--while creating unique representational and abstract artwork. This class    aids in the development of visual art skills, which can deepen secondary    visual arts education.

Are you    curious about electronics? Would you enjoy turning your friends into piano    keys, making your pencil sing, or turning your stuffed animals into    doorbells? We’ll work on fun projects like these using Makey Makey, an    electronics invention tool that lets us connect ordinary objects to a    computer, and then, make them do unusual things! Along the way, we’ll learn    about circuits, sensors & even a bit of programming.

This    Beginner/ Intermediate Guitar class is for beginners looking to build on    their skills. In this class, students are guided to move up the fretboard and    learn a variety of scales and new chord shapes ie. Bar Chords, Finger style    techniques like Strumming, Arpeggios, and Bass/Melody arrangements are    taught. Students must bring their own acoustic guitar!

Got a favorite movie? Ever wonder how the great movies got their magic? This class teaches you how! This class is an exploration of cinema style and technique through replication, imitation, creation of cinema, movies, TV, and net series. The class watches and analyzes famous movies, focusing on specific techniques, which they then replicate in class. First we watch it, then we do it! This class will use short scenes, script analysis, making short-films, lighting, camera drills, and students will practice acting/blocking tactics for movie success.

event_description: **You are adding to the wait list only**The After School program is currently full. You are adding to the wait list for the 2025-26 school year. If a spot opens up and we are able to offer you a spot, we will reach out. This afterschool program only pick up participants from Clarendon.  Our after school program is an experience that provides a safe and nurturing environment for youth in grades K-5 to develop life long recreation and leisure skills. Participants will receive homework assistance, be exposed to an environment that will promote literacy, encourage communication and empowerment skills while providing recreation activities that include sports, group games, arts and culture, community exploration and seasonal special events. All staff and volunteers receive background checks and are trained in safety skills. Start times may vary based on the school release time. The fee for the school year is $1,080. Parents will have the option to pay the entire fee upon registration. Payment plans are available. $270 is due upon registration and on the first day of October, January and March of the school year.

There is much more in Hatha yoga practice than poses. In this series, we still explore practices aimed to improve our physical well-being through asanas (poses); we also introduce practices that include pranayama (breath expansion) techniques, and finally we experience the benefits of simple meditation techniques. The intention is awareness at a physical, mental and emotional level on as well as off the mat.

Join    The Call of the Sea, St. Francis Yacht Club, and other youth,      in a three-hour voyage on Seaward, an 82-foot ship. All youth      will become sailors and scientists for the day. You will get to      help sail the ship. You will also get to learn about ecology,      marine life, sailing skills and teamwork. Seaward will do a lap      of the bay. You will board at the docks of the St. Francis Yacht      Club. The route will begin with a ride to the Golden Gate Bridge,      a view from below the bridge and then will go around Angel      Island, near Alcatraz and then, on the way back to the yacht      club, you will sail past city landmarks along the waterfront.      Every participant should bring non- skid shoes such as tennis      shoes, long pants, a jacket and layers of clothes. The Saint      Francis Yacht Club will only be a pick up/drop off point for this      class. There is no waiting area for parents or guardians. The      address is 99 Yacht Rd, San Francisco, CA 94123. This event will      go on rain or shine. Questions please contact Rex.Biteng@sfgov.      org **EACH CHILD MAY SIGN UP FOR ONLY ONE SESSION.

event_name: Woodworking in Small Spaces: Portable Workbenches!
event_description: Are you    interested in woodworking but like most city residents have limited space?    Have you built saw horses at the Randall and want to explore how to put them    to use? In this hands-on class you'll build a portable workbench that can    mount on those saw horses or at your kitchen table. From the classic hand    tools needed to make furniture (chisels, hand planes, measuring and marking    tools, and various types of saws) to small, portable power tools, you'll go    home with a deeper sense of what's possible in small spaces. Instructor Mike    Bray has decades of experience and scores of tricks and techniques for    working safely and accurately. A $100 materials fee is included in the cost    and covers the unique demands of the bench, including a bench vise, two    layers of finished ply, and hardwood framing. Prerequisite: Woodshop Safety    Orientation. Students who have not met the prerequisite will be withdrawn and    charged a 20% refund processing fee.
